            {
              "id": "4f964b1c-7ec8-3f51-a389-a71a1f67eb66",
              "name": "Non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability in util.format/console.log function",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, the `util.format/console.log` function is used to format and print strings. A non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability occurs when user-controlled data is concatenated into a string that is then processed by the `util.format/console.log` function. This can lead to various types of attacks, such as command injection, cross-site scripting (XSS), and SQL injection, depending on the context in which the function is used.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the variable `parserName` is concatenated into a string that is then passed to the `console.error` function. If an attacker can control the value of `parserName`, they could potentially inject malicious code that is then executed when the `console.error` function is called.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid including user-controlled data in strings that are processed by the `util.format/console.log` function. If this is not possible, ensure that the user-controlled data is properly sanitized and escaped before it is included in the string.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```javascript\n// Assuming e is an instance of Error\nconsole.error(`Error parsing event [parser:${encodeURIComponent(parserName)}]:`, e.message);\n```\n\nIn this fix, the `encodeURIComponent` function is used to sanitize the `parserName` variable before it is included in the string. This will prevent any potentially malicious code from being executed.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP - Command Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Command_Injection)\n- [OWASP - Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP - SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-74: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements in Output Used by a Downstream Component ('Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/74.html)\n- [CWE-116: Improper Encoding or Escaping of Output](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/116.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-74",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/74.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-116",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/116.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-74",
                  "CWE-116"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5195880b-c0e9-3d85-a865-ac44192f91ca",
              "name": "Non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability in util.format/console.log function",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability in util.format/console.log function\" in JavaScript refers to a situation where an attacker can manipulate the string that is passed to the `console.log` or `util.format` function. This can lead to various security issues such as information disclosure, log injection, or even remote code execution in some cases.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `parser.name` variable is directly embedded into the string that is passed to the `console.error` function. If an attacker can control the value of `parser.name`, they could potentially inject malicious content into the logs.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid directly embedding user-controlled variables into strings that are passed to logging functions. Instead, use parameterized messages or sanitize the user input before using it.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a safer version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```javascript\nconsole.error('matchToParser[%s]', parser.name, err);\n```\n\nIn this version, the `parser.name` variable is passed as a separate argument to the `console.error` function, which prevents it from being able to manipulate the format of the log message.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [OWASP Cheat Sheet: Logging](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Logging_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-117: Improper Output Neutralization for Logs](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/117.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-117",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/117.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-117"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8554548d-ee43-3513-85a1-fe40d82183df",
              "name": "Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the application is dynamically requiring a parser module based on a user-controlled `name` variable. If an attacker can control the `name` variable, they could potentially load arbitrary modules, leading to a variety of attacks, including XSS.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should:\n\n1. Avoid using user-controlled data to load modules dynamically. If dynamic loading is necessary, maintain a whitelist of allowed modules and reject any input that does not match the whitelist.\n2. Validate and sanitize user input. Use a known library or framework that makes it easy to escape potentially harmful characters.\n3. Use Content Security Policy (CSP) to reduce the severity of any XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere's a simple fix using a whitelist:\n\n```javascript\nconst allowedParsers = ['parser1', 'parser2', 'parser3'];\nif (!allowedParsers.includes(name)) {\n    throw new Error('Invalid parser');\n}\nconst parser = require(`./parsers/${name}`);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not explicitly require any library dependencies. However, the mitigation advice and source code fix recommendation may require the following:\n\n- A library or framework for input validation and sanitization.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Node.js Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Nodejs_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ea9c36e7-7dee-3616-a569-4867ab40526b",
              "name": "Non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability in util.format/console.log function",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability in question is related to the use of non-literal variable string concatenation in the `console.log` function. This can potentially lead to a variety of security issues, including but not limited to, code injection attacks. In this specific case, the variables `i`, `res.parserName`, and `message` are directly embedded into the string without any form of sanitization or encoding, which could lead to potential security risks if these variables contain malicious input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and/or encode user input before using it in string concatenation. This can help prevent potential code injection attacks. Additionally, it is also recommended to use parameterized queries or prepared statements whenever possible, as these can also help prevent code injection attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```javascript\nconsole.log('SNS-Record[%s]: Sending Slack message from Parser[%s]:', i, res.parserName, JSON.stringify(message, null, 2));\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, we are using `%s` as placeholders for the variables `i` and `res.parserName`. This way, the variables are not directly embedded into the string, which can help prevent potential code injection attacks.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not appear to require any specific library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [CWE-116: Improper Encoding or Escaping of Output](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/116.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-116",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/116.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-89",
                  "CWE-116"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "21173831-72b0-3f96-9f1f-9418bef37dec",
              "name": "Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when data enters a program from an untrusted source and is used to generate dynamic HTML content. The \"Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String\" vulnerability in JavaScript refers to the situation where user-controlled data is directly included in an HTML string without proper sanitization or encoding. This can allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts that can be executed in the context of the victim's browser.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the variable `path` is directly included in the string that is logged to the console. If `path` is user-controlled and not properly sanitized, this could potentially lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this type of vulnerability, you should always sanitize and/or encode user-controlled data before including it in an HTML string. Sanitization involves removing or replacing any potentially harmful characters, while encoding involves transforming these characters into a safe format that can be included in HTML without risk.\n\nIn JavaScript, you can use functions like `encodeURIComponent` or `encodeURI` to encode user-controlled data. For sanitization, you can use libraries like DOMPurify or js-xss.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the provided code snippet using `encodeURIComponent`:\n\n```javascript\nconsole.error(`event.consoleUrl(): given unparsable path: ${encodeURIComponent(path)}`);\n```\n\nPlease note that this is a basic fix and may not cover all potential edge cases. Depending on the context, you might need to use a more comprehensive sanitization or encoding method.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "24497075-2cea-3c57-ac50-aca52e9c7132",
              "name": "Non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability in util.format/console.log function",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn JavaScript, the `console.log` function is often used for debugging purposes. However, it can also be a source of security vulnerabilities if not used properly. Specifically, the non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability in `util.format/console.log` function refers to the insecure practice of concatenating non-literal variables into a string that is then passed to the `console.log` function. This can lead to various types of injection attacks, such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) or Command Injection, if the concatenated variables contain malicious user input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid directly concatenating non-literal variables into strings that are passed to the `console.log` function. Instead, use parameterized messages or sanitize the input before concatenation. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```javascript\nconsole.log('Message looked like JSON, but failed parse: %s', err.message, this.record);\n```\n\nIn this version, the `console.log` function uses a format string (`%s`) to safely insert the `err.message` into the log message. This prevents any potential injection attacks.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP - Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP - Command Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Command_Injection)\n- [CWE-117: Improper Output Neutralization for Logs](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/117.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
