            {
              "id": "ca67d425-177a-3bcf-9557-bb246f4ed809",
              "name": "Non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability in util.format/console.log function",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Non-literal variable string concatenation vulnerability in util.format/console.log function\" in JavaScript refers to a potential security risk where an attacker can inject malicious code or commands through the variables used in string concatenation within the `console.log` or `util.format` functions. This can lead to various types of attacks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), SQL Injection, and Command Injection attacks.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `console.error` function uses template literals to concatenate variables `numTries`, `waitFor`, and `e` into a string. If these variables contain user-supplied data, it could lead to a potential security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to properly sanitize and validate all user-supplied inputs. Avoid directly concatenating user-supplied data into strings that are processed by the `console.log` or `util.format` functions. Instead, use parameterized queries or prepared statements. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```javascript\nconsole.error(`[ERROR-Retryable] attempt#${sanitize(numTries)}, waiting ${sanitize(waitFor)}ms]:`, sanitize(e));\n```\n\nIn the above code, `sanitize` is a hypothetical function that you would implement to sanitize the input. The actual implementation would depend on the nature of the data.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP - Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP - SQL Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection)\n- [OWASP - Command Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Command_Injection)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)\n- [CWE-77: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in a Command ('Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/77.html)"
