            {
              "id": "ca33f41e-5a07-33e4-84bc-28773586992c",
              "name": "Non-Literal Argument in Require Function Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Non-Literal Argument in Require Function Vulnerability Detected\" vulnerability in JavaScript occurs when the argument passed to the `require` function is not a string literal, but a variable or an expression. This can potentially lead to a security risk known as \"Path Traversal\" or \"Directory Traversal\". An attacker could manipulate the value of the variable or expression to load and execute malicious code from arbitrary paths.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid using non-literal requires. Always use static paths in your `require` statements. If dynamic requires are necessary, ensure that the input is properly validated and sanitized to prevent path traversal attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using a variable in the `require` function, use a switch-case or if-else statements to determine which parser to load. Here is an example:\n\n```javascript\nlet parser;\nswitch(name) {\n    case 'parser1':\n        parser = require('./parsers/parser1');\n        break;\n    case 'parser2':\n        parser = require('./parsers/parser2');\n        break;\n    // add more cases as needed\n    default:\n        throw new Error('Invalid parser name');\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not explicitly require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-22",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html"
                  }
                ],
