            {
              "id": "ced5f3cf-53ad-3595-b2bc-7bc783a7f0dd",
              "name": "\"Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String\" vulnerability in JavaScript refers to a situation where an attacker can inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. This is possible when a web application uses input from a user within the output it generates without validating or encoding it.\n\nIn the provided code, the user-controlled data is being directly embedded into the URL string without proper sanitization. This could potentially lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks if an attacker is able to control the `region`, `logGroupName`, `filterPattern`, or `logsTimeRange` variables.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always encode user-controlled data before including it in HTML output. This can be done using JavaScript's built-in `encodeURIComponent()` function, which encodes special characters. In addition, you should also validate user input to ensure it conforms to expected formats.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe code should be fixed to encode all user-controlled data:\n\n```javascript\nreturn `https://console.aws.amazon.com/cloudwatch/home?${encodeURIComponent(region)}`\n\t\t\t+ `#logEventViewer:group=${encodeURIComponent(logGroupName)}`\n\t\t\t+ (filterPattern ? `;filter=${encodeURIComponent(filterPattern)}` : \"\")\n\t\t\t+ `;start=${encodeURIComponent(logsTimeRange.start)};end=${encodeURIComponent(logsTimeRange.end)}`;\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "81dd0bcc-840d-3b91-b522-d6c7bfef8058",
              "name": "\"Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA potential Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability from user-controlled data in HTML string exists when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML string used in a web page. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an application includes user-controllable data in a page sent to the user without properly validating or escaping that content. In this case, the vulnerability is in the JavaScript code where the user-controlled data is directly used to create a style string.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n1. Avoid inserting untrusted data into your HTML document, especially into script tags or event handlers.\n2. Use appropriate response headers to prevent any kind of XSS vulnerabilities.\n3. Validate user input: User input should always be validated before used in the application.\n4. Escape user input: If user input is used in HTML output, it should be escaped properly to prevent any malicious code execution.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the provided code, the user-controlled data `m.thickness` and `m.dashed` are directly used to create a style string. This can be fixed by properly validating and escaping the user-controlled data before using it. Here is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```javascript\nconst styles = _.map(this.metrics, m => {\n  let thickness = _.escape(m.thickness);\n  let dashed = _.escape(m.dashed);\n  return dashed ? `${thickness},5,5` : thickness;\n});\n```\n\nIn this fixed version, the `_.escape` function from lodash library is used to escape the user-controlled data.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library to execute properly:\n\n- lodash\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "45bb8a9b-8557-3f47-804d-8d44f2d69ab5",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability in User-Controlled HTML Data",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the application is taking user input directly through `event.getAccountId()` and appending it to the `author_name` string. If an attacker can control the value of `event.getAccountId()`, they could potentially inject malicious scripts that would be executed when the `author_name` string is rendered in a web page.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, you should:\n\n- Use frameworks that automatically escape XSS by design, such as Ruby on Rails, React JS, etc.\n- Escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the context in the HTML output (body, attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) will resolve Reflected and Stored XSS vulnerabilities.\n- Apply context-sensitive encoding when modifying the browser document on the client side acts against DOM XSS.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the provided code snippet, you can mitigate the XSS vulnerability by properly escaping the user input. Here's how you can do it using a simple function that replaces special characters with their HTML entities:\n\n```javascript\nfunction escapeHtml(unsafe) {\n    return unsafe\n         .replace(/&/g, \"&amp;\")\n         .replace(/</g, \"&lt;\")\n         .replace(/>/g, \"&gt;\")\n         .replace(/\"/g, \"&quot;\")\n         .replace(/'/g, \"&#039;\");\n }\n\nconst author_name = \"AWS CodeBuild\"\n\t\t+ (event.getAccountId() ? ` (${escapeHtml(event.getAccountId())})` : \"\");\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "da113207-04cb-326c-83aa-06351e88936f",
              "name": "Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when data enters a program from an untrusted source and is used to generate dynamic HTML content. The vulnerability here is that the `region` and `kind` variables in the URL string are user-controlled and not sanitized before being used to generate the URL. This could allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts into the URL, which would then be executed when the URL is accessed.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize user-controlled data before using it to generate dynamic HTML content. This can be done by encoding the data to ensure that any potentially harmful characters are not interpreted as code. \n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere's a simple fix using JavaScript's built-in `encodeURIComponent` function to sanitize the `region` and `kind` variables:\n\n```javascript\nconst findingBaseUrl = `https://console.aws.amazon.com/inspector/home?region=${encodeURIComponent(region)}#/${encodeURIComponent(kind)}`;\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b01fd755-8540-3567-a88d-010cc5e6ad94",
              "name": "\"Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when data enters a program from an untrusted source and is used to generate dynamic HTML content. The vulnerability in the provided code snippet arises from the use of user-controlled data (`field.title`) in an HTML string without proper sanitization. This could allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts that can be executed in the context of the victim's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n1. Always validate and sanitize user input: Ensure that user input matches expected patterns and does not contain malicious content.\n\n2. Use context-specific output encoding: When user input is inserted into HTML, JavaScript, CSS, or URL contexts, use context-specific encoding to prevent injection attacks.\n\n3. Use Content Security Policy (CSP): CSP is a security layer that helps detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including XSS and data injection attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nThe provided code snippet already uses a function `escape()` to sanitize `field.title`. However, it's not clear what this function does. If it's not properly implemented, it might not prevent XSS attacks. A better approach would be to use a well-tested library for HTML encoding, such as `he` for Node.js:\n\n```javascript\nconst he = require('he');\nhtml.push(`<div style=\"float:left;width:48%\"><div style=\"font-weight:bold\">${he.encode(field.title)}`);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code example requires the `he` library:\n\n```bash\nnpm install he\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "17ccad65-bc0a-31fe-89a4-feb6daddaef8",
              "name": "Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when data enters a program from an untrusted source and the data is used to generate dynamic HTML content. An attacker can inject malicious scripts into the HTML content, which will be executed by the victim's browser. In this case, the vulnerability arises from user-controlled data in an HTML string.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always escape untrusted HTTP request data based on the HTML context (body, attribute, JavaScript, CSS, or URL) that the data will be placed into. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `escape()` function is used to sanitize the `field.value` before it is inserted into the HTML string. This is a good practice as it helps to prevent XSS attacks by converting potentially harmful characters into their HTML-encoded equivalent.\n\n```javascript\nhtml.push(`</div><p style=\"margin:.5em 0\">${escape(field.value)}</p></div>`);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4d01fabc-dbdf-3f7b-a87f-b79cc1d0c6fe",
              "name": "Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when data enters a program from an untrusted source and is used to generate dynamic HTML content. The \"Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String\" vulnerability in JavaScript refers to a situation where user-controlled data is directly embedded into HTML strings. This can allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts, which will be executed in the browser of any user viewing the generated HTML.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n1. **Validate Input**: Ensure that all user-supplied input is validated before it is processed. This can help to prevent the execution of malicious scripts.\n\n2. **Encode Output**: Encode user-supplied data before it is included in HTML output. This can prevent the data from being interpreted as code by the browser.\n\n3. **Use Appropriate Response Headers**: Use HTTP headers to restrict how user-supplied data can be used in the browser. For example, the Content-Security-Policy header can be used to prevent the execution of inline scripts.\n\n4. **Use Safe APIs**: Use APIs, such as the DOM 'textContent' property or jQuery 'text' method, which automatically encode output.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink can be fixed by using the 'textContent' property to safely encode the user-controlled data:\n\n```javascript\nlet element = document.createElement('div');\nelement.textContent = `> ${field.title}: ${field.value}\\n`;\ntext.push(element);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP DOM based XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/DOM_based_XSS_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e6fb9935-6316-39be-b781-675bd2cf670e",
              "name": "XSS Vulnerability in User-Controlled HTML Data",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the application is using a template literal to include user-controlled data (`event`) in an HTML context. If the `event` data is not properly sanitized, it could lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities, it's important to:\n\n- Use a safe API which avoids the use of the interpreter entirely or provides a parameterized interface.\n- Positive or \"whitelist\" input validation can also be effective, as it prevents any input not explicitly allowed.\n- For any data that is included in an HTML context, ensure it is properly HTML encoded.\n- Use appropriate response headers to prevent any content sniffing attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe provided code is already using the `escape` function to sanitize the `event` data before it is included in the HTML context. This should mitigate the potential XSS vulnerability. However, it's important to ensure that the `escape` function is properly implemented to handle all potential edge cases.\n\n```javascript\nfunction escape(str) {\n    var div = document.createElement('div');\n    div.appendChild(document.createTextNode(str));\n    return div.innerHTML;\n}\n\nhtml.push(`<pre style=\"color:#ccc;color:rgba(0,0,0,.08);font-size:.5em;font-weight:100;line-height:.8;letter-spacing:-1px;word-break:break-all;white-space:pre-wrap;\">${escape(JSON.stringify(event))}</pre>`);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ef4e128c-6855-398a-92cc-14a986056206",
              "name": "Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. XSS is a type of injection, in which malicious scripts are injected into otherwise benign and trusted websites. In this case, the vulnerability arises from the fact that user-controlled data is being used in an HTML string without proper sanitization or encoding. This could allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts that could be executed in the context of the victim's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always encode user-controlled data before using it in an HTML context. This can be done using built-in JavaScript functions or third-party libraries that provide HTML encoding functionality. Additionally, it is also recommended to use Content Security Policy (CSP) to reduce the risk of XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe following code snippet demonstrates how to fix the vulnerability by encoding the user-controlled data:\n\n```javascript\nstr = _.replace(str, /<([^|]+)\\|([^>]+)>/g, (s, a1, a2) => `<a href=\"${encodeURI(a1)}\">${_.escape(a2)}</a>`);\n```\n\nIn this code, `encodeURI` is used to encode the URL and `_.escape` is used to escape the HTML content. Both functions help to prevent XSS attacks by ensuring that user-controlled data is properly encoded.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- Lodash (`lodash`)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4987e831-f112-3904-b0d6-11640ace5fa0",
              "name": "Potential XSS Vulnerability from User-Controlled Data in HTML String",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks. This is because it takes user-controlled data and inserts it into an HTML string without proper sanitization or encoding. An attacker could potentially inject malicious scripts into the user-controlled data, which would then be executed when the HTML string is rendered in a web browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize and/or encode user-controlled data before inserting it into an HTML string. This can be done using various methods, such as HTML encoding, JavaScript encoding, CSS encoding, URL encoding, etc. depending on the context in which the data is used.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code snippet using lodash's `_.escape` function to sanitize the user-controlled data:\n\n```javascript\nstr = _.replace(str, /(^|[^*])\\*([^*]*)\\*([^*]|$)/g, (s, a1, a2, a3) => `${a1}<b>${_.escape(a2)}</b>${a3}`);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library to execute properly:\n\n- lodash\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
